      {
        "id": 2712101,
        "name": "John B a s k a m",
        "username": "J_B_a_s_k_a_m",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/j_b_a_s_k_a_m/{size}/655_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-09-09T02:22:53.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Shared a few wines tonight.  Two of the more interesting were the 1995 Verget Chablis Grand Cru Valmur and the 2001 Mondavi Cabernet Sauvignon</p>\n<p>I was playing with time with the Verget.  I had two bottles, the first was enjoyed in 2005 and was vibrant and beautiful.  Tonights, was a dark brownish gold seemingly oxidized, but it did come around a little.  The Verget was interesting; it had almost sherry elements and some nuttiness, pear and a light lemony zing.  The wine slowly showed something, but never showed what it once had.  Ultimately, it was over-the-hill.</p>\n<p>The 2001 Mondavi was terrific.  Deep, dark red.  Meaty with Bordeaux-like flavors of leather, tobacco and dark fruit.  It was balanced and singing.  Excellent with grilled steaks.  The regular bottle showed well at age 18.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 7,
